Shouting to the world
The marketing campaign "Looks Like You Need Iceland" seems to have gotten off to a good start, and the cries and calls of nature are starting to attract people from all over the world.
You owe me an apology, I need Iceland," says a woman somewhere in the world in a comment to an ad from the Looks Like You Need Iceland marketing campaign on the video-sharing website YouTube.
Another viewer said he would keep Iceland in his heart forever and a young woman said she would have to get to Iceland as soon as possible as her boyfriend lives there.
Unfortunately, she is in the United States and is expecting to have to wait a few more months.
Another viewer asks whether the route to Iceland is open, as there are no planes.
It is not known whether he is from a different time zone.
Egill Þórðarson of the advertising agency Peel, who worked on the ads along with the international advertising agency M&C Saatchi, says the response has been beyond expectations.
I've been involved in a lot of Inspired by Iceland campaigns that have been very successful but this new campaign is already breaking records.
At its core, it's about creating PR value, that is, getting foreign media to write about the campaign, and that has gone incredibly well.
In a relatively short time, we have received coverage in over 700 media outlets around the world, which together reach over two billion people.
The value of that coverage is priced at 1.8 billion ISK.
It's not bad."
The main market is usually the United States, and the campaign has gone very well there, even though Americans are not coming to the country any time soon.
According to Egill, well-known markets such as Denmark, the UK and Germany, as well as Russia, which came as a pleasant surprise, have also done well.
Then there were reactions from foreign areas, such as India, which were not intended.
