40% of COVID-19 victims had type 2 diabetes
Devon Brumfield heard her father struggling to breathe over the phone.
Her father had diabetes and she encouraged him to seek medical help.
The next day he died.
The death was attributed to acute respiratory distress caused by the coronavirus infection.
Diabetes was listed on the death certificate as an underlying condition, and Brumfield, who also has diabetes, is terrified that she's next.
Reuters news agency says Brumfield's fears are not unfounded.
Nearly 40 percent of those who died had type 2 diabetes, according to new research funded by the U.S. government.
When the proportion of those under the age of 65 is considered, it rises to half.
The CDC study looked at more than 10,000 people in 15 states who died from COVID-19 between February and May.
Jonathan Wortham, an infectious disease expert at the CDC, says the findings are striking, especially for people with type 2 diabetes and their loved ones.
Reuters, which commissioned the poll, said the responses from the 12 countries that responded pointed to similar proportions.
Ten states, including California, Arizona and Colorado, are not yet reporting underlying conditions.
Diabetes was already an epidemic in slow motion.
Now, COVID-19 has broken through like a powerful tsunami," Reuters quoted Elbert Huang, director of the Center for Chronic Disease Research and Policy at the University of Chicago, as saying.
Diabetes is more common among blacks and people of South American descent, who have also been hit harder by the coronavirus.
One of the best defenses for those with type 2 diabetes is to keep the disease in check with exercise, a healthy diet, and help from healthcare professionals.
However, the coronavirus pandemic has made it difficult for many to maintain a routine.
Then there is the high price of insulin, which has forced some to keep going to work and risk exposure to the virus.
Reuters points out that U.S. authorities may have been aware of the risk diabetics face from the virus.
During the SARS outbreak in 2003, more than 20% of them had the disease, and during the swine flu outbreak in 2009, this group was three times more likely to be hospitalized.
When MERS emerged in 2012, one study found that 60 percent of those who died or were admitted to intensive care had diabetes.
Charles S. Dela Cruz, a scientist at Yale University, says that because of the lingering effects of the COVID-19 virus, the pandemic has revealed a number of previously unknown side effects.
I fear we will see a tsunami of problems when this is over," said Andrew Bolton, chairman of the International Diabetes Federation.
Doctors have warned that the coronavirus pandemic could lead to an increase in complications related to diabetes, including kidney disease and kidney failure.
New research also suggests that the coronavirus may lead to an increase in diabetes cases.
Reuters says scientists are trying to understand the links between the coronavirus and type 2 diabetes.
The virus attacks the heart, lungs and kidneys, organs that are already weakened in many people with diabetes.
High levels of glucose and lipids in diabetics can cause a true "cytokine storm," as it is called when the immune system overreacts and attacks the body.
Damaged endothelial cells can also lead to the formation of blood clots, which can be fatal.
It's all one big puzzle," Dela Cruz said.
It's all interconnected."
