Ambassadorless for five years since 2009
U.S. Ambassador to Iceland Jeffrey Gunter Ross is in the spotlight after CBS reported this morning that he requested an armed bodyguard because he feared for his life.
However, it has not gone smoothly for the President of the United States to appoint an ambassador to Iceland.
Since Carol Van Voorst stepped down as U.S. ambassador in late April 2009, the country has been without an ambassador for 62 months, more than five years.
Van Voorst resigned under unusual circumstances, but Kastljós reported in 2009 that she should have received the Order of the Falcon.
On her way to a farewell meeting with the President of Iceland, she received a phone call from the Presidential Office informing her that she would not be awarded the title.
After leaving Iceland, she taught international relations at the Army War College.
Sixteen months later, Van Voorst's successor took office in September 2010.
This was partly due to the fact that Robert S. Connan had been appointed as ambassador but then withdrew.
Finally, Louis Ariega, who had worked in the Foreign Service for a decade, took over.
He then retired in the fall of 2013 and took up the post of ambassador to Guatemala.
Then came another period without an ambassador.
Robert Barber was confirmed by the U.S. Senate in January 2015 and came on board shortly thereafter, filling a gap of 13 months without an ambassador.
Barber was a political appointee but not a diplomat, having worked as a lawyer and supported Barack Obama's presidential campaign.
He left office on January 20, 2017, when Donald Trump took office, as is customary for politically appointed ambassadors.
Trump's administration has been unusually slow to appoint both ambassadors and senior officials in Washington.
Two years later, the U.S. Congress called Jeffrey Ross Gunter to a hearing to grill him and confirm him as ambassador to Iceland.
In his testimony to the committee, he said he had never been to Iceland but often to Western Europe, and his late wife was Dutch.
Gunter is a political appointee, was previously a dermatologist in California, and has been prominent in the Republican Jewish Coalition.
The group was founded by casino mogul Sheldon Adelson, an ardent supporter of Donald Trump.
Gunter arrived in Iceland in May 2019, at a time when no ambassador had been in the country since early 2017, for two years and four months, which is the longest gap in Icelandic diplomatic history.
The reason is both how long the Trump administration has taken to nominate people to key positions, as well as the fact that the U.S. Congress has dragged its feet on confirming ambassadors in recent years.
Since 2009, Iceland has been without an ambassador for a total of over five years.
However, this has not prevented the embassy from carrying out construction work, which recently opened a new headquarters at Engjateig.
Construction is estimated to have cost around 6.5 billion won, with thick security walls surrounding the building and bulletproof glass in all the windows.
However, it does not seem to have been enough to reassure the current ambassador, who is said to fear for his life and has requested an armed bodyguard.
