Pensions and long shadows
2019 was a landmark year in the history of pension funds in Iceland.
Officials had indeed received pensions from the Danish king since the 19th century, but in 1919 a pension fund for civil servants was established, which eventually became a pension fund for all public employees.
The basis for the current occupational pension schemes of general wage earners was then laid with the all-encompassing collective bargaining agreements on the labour market in 1969, which provided for occupational pension schemes with compulsory membership and full-fledged fund accumulation from the beginning of 1970.
In 1974, laws were passed based on these agreements and the pension system continued to grow.
The employees' pension system was not the only radical change that the labor movement of the 20th century brought about through its struggle for wages.
Unemployment insurance had been won in a similar way in the famous strikes of 1955, and the union also gradually won its demands for sick leave, health insurance, significant holiday rights, shorter working hours, improvements in housing and so on.
All of these rights came at great cost and with great struggle, but in retrospect they proved to be a much greater and more lasting gain than the increase in the amount of money in the pay envelope, which disappeared just as quickly in the heat of inflation that characterized the post-war period until 1990, as many remember.
The lead-up to the establishment of universal pension funds in 1969 was both long and complex.
Although it was eventually agreed that the funds would in fact be the property of the fund members, the labor movement had to accept that the boards would be composed of representatives of employers and fund members in equal numbers.
In the following years after the founding of the funds, the demand for a majority of workers in the boards of the funds was often discussed in trade unions, but it never came to fruition, and so we are still left with the abnormal situation that the representatives of the funds are not in the majority in the boards of the funds.
Section 36 of Act No. 129/1997 on compulsory pension funding and the operation of pension funds deals with the investment policy of the funds.
Paragraph 1 of Article 1 states that "the pension fund shall have the interests of the members as its guiding principle."
Paragraph 5 also states: "The pension fund shall set ethical guidelines for its investments."
In the shareholder policy of the Lífeyrissjóður verslunarmanna, among other things, the following provisions follow on from the aforementioned legal provisions:
The pension fund is a signatory to the United Nations Principles for Responsible Investment (UN PRI), along with many of the largest pension funds and institutional investors in North America and Europe.
The guidelines discuss how an emphasis on environmental and social issues, as well as good corporate governance, can contribute to improved investment outcomes for funds.
In this way, the interests of investors and the goals of society in a broader sense can be reconciled.
LV believes it is important for companies, especially those listed on the stock exchange, to have a public policy on: good corporate governance, remuneration, social responsibility and environmental issues.
Iceland's largest pension fund, Gildi, has adopted a "responsible investment policy" which contains similar provisions.
This is all revisited here as an introduction to the latest fashion word in Icelandic, "shadow management".
As the term is new in the language, it is not surprising that it has not been fully defined, but the following definition seems to be the most widely accepted: Shadow-directing is when a union leader tells the media that he intends to instruct union representatives on a pension board to vote a certain way on a particular issue.
If they do not comply, they will be removed from the board at the first opportunity.
However, if the leader does not take this to the media and does not talk about the dismissal, it is not "shadow management" either, since such communication between people is of course always present in the financial world, as in other places.
I leave it to the reader to decide which way is "more sinister."
As of the morning of Saturday, July 25, 2020, there are two men who have tried to shape this definition.
They are Hörður Ægisson, journalist at Fréttablaðið, and Ásgeir Jónsson, Central Bank Governor.
The trigger for both was Icelandair CEO Birkir Hólm Guðnason's announcement that he intended to tear up the company's collective bargaining agreements with flight attendants and cabin crew (fire them), and Ragnar Þór Ingólfsson, chairman of the Reykjavík Retailers' Union, sent out a message to the union's representatives on the board of the Lífeyrissjóður verslunarmanna pension fund urging them not to support the fund's possible purchase of shares in the company, or else they might be sacked.
A little later, Bogi Nils withdrew his decision and Ragnar Þór followed suit with his recommendations, of course based on Bogi's decision.
Nonetheless, Hörður and Ásgeir saw fit to editorialise on the matter in the Friday edition of Fréttablaðið, using big words about shadow governance, law-breaking and the need for legislative change.
There, a little sparrow certainly had to lift a heavy burden, although the blessed sparrow was in the process of being wiped out.
Given the importance of the matter, let's focus on the substance at the end.
I have described the relevant provisions of the Pension Fund Law above.
This means that fund managers must act in the best interests of fund members and have ethical considerations in their investment decisions, and this is further elaborated in the regulations of both Gildi and Lífeyrissjóður verslunarmanna, as I mentioned.
Pension funds, however, SHOULD NOT ONLY look at short-term profitability in their investments.
Such a policy would be extremely dangerous and there are plenty of examples from the past where large loans from banks and funds have flowed to unscrupulous adventurers and environmental disasters, with disastrous consequences.
Icelandair's CEO was obviously on thin ice when he thought of wiping out an entire group of employees, reducing the goodwill the company has enjoyed in the Icelandic market and weakening its position towards investors.
Fortunately, he saw the error of his ways and retracted.
Time will tell whether this is enough to justify the pension funds' investment in the company.
