Whole apartment block collapses in city centre
Romanian workers live for free at Dunhaga 18–20.
Meanwhile, owners are seeking building permits for renovations, but their applications have languished in the system for more than three years.
In one of the oldest, greenest and most expensive areas of Reykjavík, a magnificent apartment building stands on three floors.
The ground floor of the building has about 600 square metres of retail space.
Behind the house are the entrances to two stairwells, each containing four fairly spacious apartments.
They range from 93 to 130 square meters, though most are over 100.
The house has a long history.
It was built in 1959 and has housed a video rental, Skóstofan, the dairy Mjólkursamsölunnar, Jóa gunsmith, a fish shop, and most recently Háskólaprent.
The house, to put it mildly, has seen better days.
The house is now severely damaged, as can be seen in the accompanying pictures.
The owner of the building is D18 ehf.
The owners of D18 ehf. are Magnús Magnússon and Guðrún Helga Lárusdóttir, among others, according to the company register.
Magnús led a group of owners of Borgun and was the representative of the Borgun holding company.
Stálskip ehf. is one of the owners of the holding company Borgun.
Stálskip ehf. is an investment company owned by Guðrún Helga Lárusdóttir and her children.
Guðrún also owns a third of D18 ehf.
Guðrún and her husband, Ágúst Guðmundur Sigurðsson, once owned the fishing company Stálskip.
D18 ehf. bought the house in the summer of 2009 and has done little to maintain it since then.
Neighbors say the condition of the house has deteriorated steadily over the years, especially in recent years.
On a Facebook page for the neighbourhood, one resident said the house had "not been particularly lively in recent years."
The fact that the owners have been trying to change the house and the lot for several years may play a role.
Other neighbors say the house has not been in good shape for a long time.
It's long overdue to do something nice with this spot and it's sad that it's taken this long."
He also says that he is annoyed at the owners of the house for not getting on with it, finding a common ground with the neighbours of the house and stopping this "legal bickering".
Just do it in consultation with the community around here so we can get it done and get it done."
The "legal wrangling" the resident refers to is the planning process for the site, which has been going on at least since 2017.
The owners of Dunhaga 18 and 20 then applied for permission to build a floor on top of the existing apartment building and behind the building, a new lift house and a single-storey extension with a basement.
The building permit granted for the project was appealed to the Board of Appeal for Environment and Natural Resources, and the board ruled that the permit was invalid because the project was not in accordance with the zoning plan and the notification to the neighbors was insufficient.
Reykjavíkurborg started the zoning process and completed it with an announcement in Stjórnartíðindum in July last year.
That scheme was also challenged and the committee struck it down in March 2020.
At this point, nearly three years had passed since the original application for a building permit, and the owners of the house were back at square one.
By this time, the house had fallen into disrepair and the neighbours were getting tired of it.
When DV asked the neighbors of the house about the situation, the answers were varied.
Some understood the owners' intentions, others did not.
Some directed their anger at the city, others did not.
Others were just angry, but not necessarily at anyone in particular.
Others said the parking spaces were a headache, but neighbors have been using the unused parking spaces of Dunhaga 18-20 for their vehicles.
One complainant in the case said he was tired of the bureaucracy:
To have to go through the process three times is unbelievable.
It's as if Reykjavíkurborg doesn't know how to read."
Today the house stands empty, abandoned and neglected.
A memorial to the ephemeral city administration and the owner's and many years of work now at the beginning.
When a reporter arrived at Dunhaga 18, he was greeted by open doors and a pile of garbage.
A Playstation console and a recent television lay among other rubbish on the ground - victims of Icelandic summer heat.
The old office of Háskólaprent was open, and there were a lot of cats from the smell of it.
It is clear that someone has taken up residence in one corner, but no one is visible.
Stacks of sofas and beds and a few shelves of geological field notebooks, presumably destined for a book, loomed.
The stairwells of the apartment building were also open and full of life.
The reporter was fortunate enough to run into a resident of the other one.
The Romanians were cooking a potato dish for dinner and invited the reporter in.
The Romanians work for the employment agency Ztrongforce ehf.
They have been there for some time and, according to DV, the company has not paid for the premises except for heating and electricity.
Due to the condition of the house, it is not justifiable to charge rent.
From the mailboxes in the hallway of the house, it is clear that a number of foreign workers have lived there in recent months.
Staffing agencies have not been immune to the effects of the Covid-19 pandemic, as the downturn in tourism has led to a downturn in the construction sector, and these two sectors have been the most prolific users of staffing agencies.
Nonetheless, the residents of Dunhaga 18 seemed to have plenty to do and hung their work clothes and gloves in the common area to dry after a long day of work in the rain.
It should be noted that despite the dilapidated state of the house, the apartment that the boys shared appeared to be well maintained.
When the reporter said goodbye to the Romanian boys, the irony suddenly hit him: In the best place in Reykjavík, a 1,500-square-meter property is falling apart.
The owners want to improve the house and the neighbors want to improve the condition, but they disagree on the definition of "improvement."
In the middle sits the city's planning department, a victim of endless appeals and complaints in the planning process and a slow-moving Environmental Board of Appeal.
The house is then inhabited by Romanian workers, perhaps the very ones who will improve the situation when the Icelanders stop arguing.
The article originally appeared in DV's weekend edition on July 17.
