A new variant rather than a new type of virus
A new virus just means it was an individual who came from abroad.
This is not something that has been brewing domestically," says Már Kristjánsson, head of the infectious diseases department at Landspítalinn, about the news that "a new type of virus" has been detected in Iceland.
Three domestic cases were detected yesterday and two at the border.
One of those who tested positive had taken part in the Rey Cup football tournament, but the source of the infection is unknown and contact tracing is ongoing.
In addition, a case was detected in an individual who arrived in the country on July 15, and two who were in contact with him have begun to show symptoms of COVID-19.
Yesterday, a case was detected that is related to the case reported yesterday, and after sequencing at deCODE genetics, a "new type of virus that has not been detected before" was found.
Contact tracing is complete in relation to that case.
Már points out that this is not a new virus, but the same virus that has spread all over the world, i.e. the new coronavirus SARS-CoV-2.
It is more accurate to talk about a new variant of that virus rather than a new type of virus.
Asked what it means and whether it could say anything about the start of a second wave of the epidemic, Már says that, as things stand, it is a single case and it may be that nothing more will come of it.
But on the other hand, if there are cases in the country that are not connected abroad and have the same genotype as this particular variant, then it would be possible to draw the conclusion [about a second wave] but it is premature at the moment, Már explains.
