100 days to go until the election
There are 100 days until Americans go to the polls and elect a president for four years.
Donald Trump is seeking re-election, but he faces an uphill battle.
Joe Biden, the presumptive Democratic nominee, has a wide lead over Trump nationally, according to polls.
According to a new AP poll, a record number of Americans believe the country is on the wrong track.
Trump's response to the new coronavirus pandemic is also very unpopular, and more Americans than ever believe that the president has handled the economy badly.
Specifically, only two in ten Americans say the United States is on the right track.
32 percent say they approve of Trump's handling of the pandemic and 48 percent say he has handled the economy well.
It was 56 percent in March and 67 percent in January.
According to the FiveThirtyEight average, Biden has 49.9 percent of the national vote while Trump has 41.9 percent.
Trump himself has tried to shift attention away from his handling of the pandemic to Biden, stoking so-called culture wars and promising a law-and-order agenda.
Biden's campaign, however, is making a concerted effort to keep the focus on Trump and believes it has a good chance of winning if the election is really about how Trump has done his job over the past four years.
Trump's unpopularity also appears to be dragging down Republican lawmakers, and Democrats are even hoping to gain a majority in the U.S. Senate, which had previously been considered highly unlikely.
Politico reported last week that if the parties and candidates were to maintain their current levels of support, the Republican Party would suffer its worst defeat in decades.
The suburbs have proved to be particularly bad for the party in the 2016 general election, and it looks like that trend will continue.
Trump has in recent days sought to scare suburban voters into following him, including by saying that if Biden were to become president, he would destroy suburbs across the United States and stoke racial divisions.
Among other things, Trump has scrapped an Obama-era rule designed to increase diversity in suburbs.
He then urged "suburban housewives" in the United States to read an op-ed by a former New York deputy secretary of state, who argued that Biden would destroy the suburbs, which Trump endorsed.
Biden will destroy your neighborhoods and the American Dream.
I will keep it, and even make it better!" the president said.
Suburban Americans are an ever-growing voting bloc.
According to NPR, they are half of all American voters.
Since George W. Bush was re-elected in 2004, the candidate who has won a majority of this group's votes has become president.
With the exception of 2012, when Mitt Romney received a majority of the vote from this group but lost to Barack Obama.
Polls have shown that despite Trump winning a narrow majority in the suburbs in 2016, his support there has dropped significantly.
While the polls vary, Biden has been ahead of Trump by about 15 percentage points in recent weeks.
