After the final decision was made to postpone the Olympics, an event that has only been disrupted by world wars until now, the president of the International Olympic Committee said the famous Olympic flame would be "the light at the end of the tunnel," referring to the coronavirus pandemic that the world is going through together.
Athletes have an extra year to prepare and officials in Japan are footing the bill for the delay.
Everyone keeps their head, however, as a lot is at stake.
When it was announced that Tokyo in Japan would be the venue for this year's Olympics, the cheers of the Japanese delegation were genuine.
They cried and laughed alternately, as Tokyo had applied to host the games in 2016 but lost out to Rio de Janeiro in Brazil.
This time, Tokyo and Japan would bask in the world's attention.
The games were originally scheduled to take place from 24 July to 9 August but have been postponed for a year and will now start on 23 July 2021 and end on 8 August.
If it is not possible to hold the games then, if the coronavirus is still a major threat, the games will be cancelled.
But no one wants to think that thought to the end.
The Olympics are no ordinary sporting event.
Nothing is spared, the show must always be spectacular and strive to top the last one.
The selection of a city for the Olympic Games is based on the evaluation of the cities' presentations by the selection committee.
The more impressive the presentation, the greater the chance of winning the prize.
Tokyo spent $150 million to try to get the 2016 Olympics, or about 200 billion yen.
For the second time, when bidding for the 2020 games, 75 million dollars, about 10 billion króna, was put into the campaign.
In 2013, when it was decided that Tokyo would host the games this year, the Japanese government had already spent 30 billion ISK on the project.
But that amount is just a drop in the ocean compared to what it costs to build an Olympic village, venues and generally strengthen the country's infrastructure to host such an event, prepare for it and hold the games themselves.
Organizers in Japan have said the Tokyo Olympics, which would have been underway this week but was postponed for a year because of the coronavirus, would have cost $12.6 billion.
However, in a report released by the Japanese Audit Board at the end of last year, it was revealed that the cost was actually double that figure.
It is likely that the cost of postponing the games will not be fully known, but it has been estimated that it could cost between two and six billion dollars on top of the original cost.
The total cost to the Japanese Olympic Committee and Japanese taxpayers could range from $15 billion to $30 billion.
The numbers are so high that all the tax revenue of the Icelandic state would barely cover half an Olympic Games, based on the lowest possible cost.
The Olympics are an event of that magnitude that they have often been the subject of economists, who try to crunch the numbers and look at the benefits and costs of hosting the games.
In short, a lot of people seem to have come to the conclusion that the economic effects of the Olympics are far from positive for the cities that host them.
There are some short-term effects, such as a large increase in jobs for a short period of time, but in the long term, cities are often left with a debt burden and high operating costs for little-used infrastructure.
Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, is saddled with significant debt from the 2016 Games and has struggled to maintain the large sports venues built for the Games.
Analysis of figures after the London 2012 Games revealed that only 10 per cent of those who got jobs linked to the Olympics in the city were previously unemployed.
This means that there were not many new jobs created.
In general, cities have not fared particularly well financially from hosting the Olympics because of the crushing cost of the infrastructure built for the games.
However, the benefits are often said to lie in increased tourist traffic visiting the Olympic cities after the games, although there is much uncertainty about the 2021 games.
It is also unclear whether it will be possible to accommodate the usual number of spectators.
The main thing, though, is the honour of being chosen, which is hard to put a price on.
Indeed, despite the enormous cost, it can also be said that the joy the Games bring is not something that can be put a price on.
But while the show is often spectacular and nothing is spared, this is not just about money.
It is the sporting heroes who are in the spotlight.
For some athletes, the postponement is a blessing in disguise.
Australian five-time Olympian and gold medallist in her event at the 2016 Games, Chloe Esposito, is also pregnant and would have missed out on this summer's action but is hopeful of being in peak form for the 2021 Games.
She is therefore among those athletes who are quite happy with the postponement, for understandable reasons.
For those athletes who had planned to retire after this year's games, the postponement means that some of them will now retire before the games take place.
They simply don't trust their bodies to go through another year of intense training.
Few athletes captured the hearts of spectators at the 2016 Rio Olympics quite like gymnast Simone Biles.
She came home with four gold medals and one bronze.
Biles has done a number of interviews in her native United States recently to discuss the Olympics.
She's aiming for the 2021 Olympics, but she's not sure if she'll still be at the top of her game by then, as she'll be 24 by then.
While it is generally not considered a high age, it is above average for an elite gymnast.
It's a sensitive subject," Biles said, smiling, in an interview published on the IOC's Instagram account when asked if she hopes to match her haul from the 2016 Rio Games.
I don't even know if I'm going to be on top after another year of training," Biles said.
She has previously spoken about how her body can no longer cope with the demands of gymnastics.
Nonetheless, she is training hard for the 2021 Olympics.
Biles admits it was an uncomfortable feeling to have to suddenly stop training when the pandemic was at its peak and the gym was closed.
There were no exemptions for Biles any more than there were for anyone else while all athletic facilities were closed for seven weeks.
All of her Olympic gold medals couldn't buy her any more access than anyone else, she had to find other ways to stay in shape like everyone else.
The basic form is certainly better than most people.
We have a busy schedule now.
It was hard to start training again after the gym reopened.
We started slowly but we're back up to full speed and I'll be increasing my training gradually as the year goes on.
Of course, we don't know exactly how these games will be or if they will be held, but we are training as if they will be, we can't do anything else.
I've put in too much work to walk away from the sport now," Biles said.
As with her, and others, there is a nagging doubt or perhaps more of an awareness that the games might not be held at all in 2021.
But predicting it is impossible.
Nobody knows how the COVID-19 pandemic will be in July 2021 and there is nothing else to do but prepare for the Olympics as if they will be held a year from now.
Maybe the Olympic flame will be the light at the end of the Covid tunnel.
Wedding postponed due to pandemic
Modern Family actress Sarah Hyland has decided to postpone her wedding due to the coronavirus.
She was set to marry former Bachelorette contestant Wells Adams this summer.
I think there are more important things to think about right now," the actress told People.
We definitely want to get married one day and have our dream wedding and have all our loved ones there.
But we decided to put it on hold and focus on what's important right now, which is helping to share information about the importance of wearing masks and staying home.
I'm more focused on world affairs than wedding plans these days.
There's a lot going on and we need to focus on what's happening in the world."
